1 Read in the data

The first thing you need to do is read in the provided data into an R dataframe1. The file containing the data is clinical-study.csv.

Use the read_csv() function. You should only need to provide it with one argument: a string representing the filename/path of the .csv file you want to read in.

Recall that R can store values, including the output of functions, in objects. For example, my_result <- sqrt(4) stores the output of calling the square root function on 4 in an object called my_result.

Chapter 4 of R for Data Science has a concise explanation of this.

Be sure to store the dataframe in an object with a suitable name in snake_case, such as study_df.

If youâve successfully read the data from the file into an object, you should see something like this in the Environment window in the top right:

Youâll occasionally want to wipe all data currently stored in the environment. For example, if you want to re-run (i.e.Â source) your whole script, to ensure no conflict with some data already being present.

3 Clean up the data

Cleaning the data is an unglamorous but necessary task. There are several ways it should be cleaned up. Letâs go through them one by one.

3.1 Rename columns

This is a straightforward but important one. Column names should be in snake_case and be descriptive without being too long. For example:

# Good column names
"blood_pressure"
"white_blood_count"

# Bad column names
"Blood Pressure"
"bloodPressure"
"WBC"
"White_Blood_Count"

The function called (you guessed it) rename() is simple to use, simply pass the dataframe as the first argument, followed by the column(s) you want renaming in the form new_name = oldName like so:

rename(
  starwars,
  hair_colour = hair_color,
  eye_colour = eye_color,
  weight = mass
)

Refer back to the data dictionary provided in the main document and decide which columns in our data should be renamed per the best practice described above.

Letâs also rename âsubject_idâ to âparticipant_idâ, since that is the term generally used nowadays.

3.2 Filter out irrelevant data

Did you notice that there are a small number of patients of a very young age? Looks like some data from a paedeatrics study has accidentally gotten mixed in! You need to remove them. This is a job for filter() - see how we can use it on the Star Wars data if weâre looking for droids:

filter(starwars, species == "Droid")

Note the second argument of the function is a condition on one or more of the columns, which specifies which rows we want to keep. Try playing around with different conditions. You can then ensure the dataframe only retains adult data.

3.3 Remove duplicates

You may have also noticed that the first and second rows are identical, including the subject_id. Looks like someone accidentally added the same data twice. How can you remove such duplicates? Are there any others?

If youâre particularly eagle-eyed, you have spotted a small number of NA values in one of the columns. How can you deal with these?

Click for a hint

Try using the replace_na() function. As for what value to actually replace them with, there are multiple options. If youâre unsure look at the other values and pick a single value to insert.

4.1 The pipe operator %>%

In the examples thus far weâve used the assignment operator <- more than we actually needed. Thereâs a convenient option which can replace it in some cases: %>% the pipe operator. It takes whatever is placed on the left side of it and inserts it as the first argument to the whatever function is placed on the right side.

See Chapter 18 of R for Data Science for a more detailed explanation.

5 Aggregate the data

You can understand more about data by aggregating it. This involves splitting the data into a number of groups based on a chosen column (or columns), then applying a function (e.g.Â mean()) to each group and finally combining the results. This can be accomplished using the function group_by(). Itâs worth taking a few minutes to look over this short article on how to use the function. Pay particular attention to the section titled Verbs.

Letâs look at our own example using the diamonds dataset from Tidyverse:

head(diamonds, 7)
# A tibble: 7 Ã 10
  carat cut       color clarity depth table price     x     y     z
  <dbl> <ord>     <ord> <ord>   <dbl> <dbl> <int> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
1  0.23 Ideal     E     SI2      61.5    55   326  3.95  3.98  2.43
2  0.21 Premium   E     SI1      59.8    61   326  3.89  3.84  2.31
3  0.23 Good      E     VS1      56.9    65   327  4.05  4.07  2.31
4  0.29 Premium   I     VS2      62.4    58   334  4.2   4.23  2.63
5  0.31 Good      J     SI2      63.3    58   335  4.34  4.35  2.75
6  0.24 Very Good J     VVS2     62.8    57   336  3.94  3.96  2.48
7  0.24 Very Good I     VVS1     62.3    57   336  3.95  3.98  2.47

Thereâs a column for each of the 4 Cs of diamonds, as well as price and some data on the shape and dimensions. Suppose we wanted to compare the price for different clarity levels. In that case we should group by clarity and calculate the mean for each group, like so:

diamonds %>%
  group_by(clarity) %>%
  summarise(average_price = mean(price))
# A tibble: 8 Ã 2
  clarity average_price
  <ord>           <dbl>
1 I1              3924.
2 SI2             5063.
3 SI1             3996.
4 VS2             3925.
5 VS1             3839.
6 VVS2            3284.
7 VVS1            2523.
8 IF              2865.

Note the use of the summarise() function together with mean() to create a new column called average_price in the resulting aggregated data. But somethingâs off. The better clarity diamonds (IF, VVS1, VVS2 being the top 3) have a lower average price than the worse clarity diamonds. That doesnât make sense! Moreover, we can trust the data as it originates from a reputable source. So what gives?

Letâs try controlling for the other 3 Cs, making our group by more interesting:

diamonds %>%
  filter((color == "D") & (cut == "Ideal")) %>%
  mutate(price_per_carat = price / carat) %>%
  group_by(clarity) %>%
  summarise(
    num_diamonds = n(),
    average_price_per_carat = mean(price_per_carat)
  )
# A tibble: 8 Ã 3
  clarity num_diamonds average_price_per_carat
  <ord>          <int>                   <dbl>
1 I1                13                   2898.
2 SI2              356                   3453.
3 SI1              738                   3399.
4 VS2              920                   3521.
5 VS1              351                   3969.
6 VVS2             284                   5024.
7 VVS1             144                   4861.
8 IF                28                   9034.

Do you follow all the steps? First we filtered to only include diamonds with colour âDâ and an âIdealâ cut. Then we calculated the price per carat, to control for certain clarity levels simply having larger (i.e.Â more expensive) diamonds in the data. And finally we grouped by clarity and calculated the average price per carat (we also counted the number of rows using n()). Now we can clearly see that the better clarity diamonds are more expensive!

See if you can now apply the same methodology to the data for this clinical study. Try aggregating the data to learn the following:

  1. How does the age of patients compare for the two treatment groups? Does it match what youâd expect? What about the weight?

  2. How does protein concentration compare for responders vs.Â non-responders?

  3. How do the two treatment groups compare in terms of response? (A key question!)

Click for a hint

It may not be enough to only group by one variableâ¦

  1. How does protein concentration compare for combinations of treatment group and response?

6 Visualise the data

Aggregating data is all well and good but tables arenât as easy on the eye as visuals. Enter Tidyverseâs sublime package ggplot. At this point we highly recommend reading Chapter 3 of R for Data Science as it walks the reader through using ggplot fantastically.

Letâs create an example plot of our own using the diamonds data from above:

best_diamonds <- diamonds %>%
  filter(
    (clarity %in% c("IF", "VVS1", "VVS2"))
    & (color == "D")
    & (cut == "Ideal")
  )

ggplot(best_diamonds, aes(carat, price, colour = clarity)) +
  geom_point()

We can clearly see that when it comes to price IF > VVS1 > VVS2 for a given carat. We can also easily see that there arenât many diamonds between 0.75 and 1.0 carat. Moreover, above 1.0 carat the price difference between the three clarity levels increases, perhaps because such diamonds are rarer. The power of plots!

How about one more? Letâs opt for a boxplot (AKA box-and-whisker diagram) this time since we have categorical (clarity, colour, cut) and continuous variables (carat, price). Itâd be interesting to see to what extent colour affects price:

coloured_diamonds <- diamonds %>%
  filter(
    (clarity %in% c("VVS2"))
    & (cut == "Ideal")
  ) %>%
  mutate(price_per_carat = price / carat)

ggplot(coloured_diamonds, aes(color, price_per_carat)) +
  geom_boxplot()

It seems like there isnât a strong trend here, although we can see that the D-F (colourless) diamonds are a bit pricier than the G-J (near-colourless) diamonds.

Now itâs time for you to create some plots!

Have some fun trying to visualise the following:

  1. How age and weight are distributed amongst the patients.
    1. Can you also make it easy to see the difference between sexes on the same plot?
  2. How BMI may be related to response.
    1. Does treatment group impact this relationship?
  3. How protein concentration is (or isnât) correlated with response.
    1. And does treatment group impact this relationship?
Tip

Refer to section 3.5 in R for Data Science. You can use the method described there to visualise the difference between the two treatment groups.

7 Modelling

Advanced task

This will require you to have some knowledge of mathematical modelling, so donât worry if you find it too tricky, you can skip it. Chapters 22-25 of R for Data Science serve as a great introduction.

Try to create a simple model, such as a decision tree, capable of predicting whether a given patient will respond or not.

A few considerations:

  • Youâll need to split the dataset into training and test data, the caret package can help here with its createDataPartition() function.
  • Be sure to include only the columns which are relevant for modelling, e.g.Â subject_id can be safely discarded.
  • For decision trees the package rpart is a good choice, along with rpart.plot to actually view a trained tree!
  • A more sophisticated option is a random forest. This involves training a collection of decision trees, each on a different subset of the data, and then selecting the best one. Try the package randomForest.

Happy Modelling!

## Aggregate the data

You can understand more about data by *aggregating* it. This involves splitting the data into a number of groups based on a chosen column (or columns), then applying a function (e.g. `mean()`) to each group and finally combining the results. This can be accomplished using the function `group_by()`. It's worth taking a few minutes to look over [this short article](https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/articles/grouping.html) on how to use the function. Pay particular attention to the section titled *Verbs*.

Let's look at our own example using the `diamonds` dataset from Tidyverse:

```{R}
head(diamonds, 7)
```

There's a column for each of the 4 Cs of diamonds, as well as price and some data on the shape and dimensions. Suppose we wanted to compare the price for different clarity levels. In that case we should *group by clarity* and calculate the mean for each group, like so:

```{R}
diamonds %>%
  group_by(clarity) %>%
  summarise(average_price = mean(price))
```

Note the use of the `summarise()` function together with `mean()` to create a new column called average_price in the resulting aggregated data. But something's off. The better clarity diamonds (IF, VVS1, VVS2 being the top 3) have a lower average price than the worse clarity diamonds. That doesn't make sense! Moreover, we can trust the data as it originates from a reputable source. So what gives?

Let's try controlling for the other 3 Cs, making our group by more interesting:

```{R}
diamonds %>%
  filter((color == "D") & (cut == "Ideal")) %>%
  mutate(price_per_carat = price / carat) %>%
  group_by(clarity) %>%
  summarise(
    num_diamonds = n(),
    average_price_per_carat = mean(price_per_carat)
  )
```

Do you follow all the steps? First we filtered to only include diamonds with colour "D" and an "Ideal" cut. Then we calculated the price per carat, to control for certain clarity levels simply having larger (i.e. more expensive) diamonds in the data. And finally we grouped by clarity and calculated the average price per carat (we also counted the number of rows using `n()`). Now we can clearly see that the better clarity diamonds are more expensive!

See if you can now apply the same methodology to the data for this clinical study. Try aggregating the data to learn the following:

1. How does the age of patients compare for the two treatment groups? Does it match what you'd expect? What about the weight?

2. How does protein concentration compare for responders vs. non-responders?

3. How do the two treatment groups compare in terms of response? (A key question!)

::: {.callout-note collapse="true"}
## Click for a hint

It may not be enough to only group by one variable...
:::

4. How does protein concentration compare for combinations of treatment group and response?


## Visualise the data

Aggregating data is all well and good but tables aren't as easy on the eye as visuals. Enter Tidyverse's sublime package *ggplot*. At this point we highly recommend reading [Chapter 3 of *R for Data Science*](https://r4ds.had.co.nz/data-visualisation.html) as it walks the reader through using ggplot fantastically.

Let's create an example plot of our own using the diamonds data from above:

```{R}
best_diamonds <- diamonds %>%
  filter(
    (clarity %in% c("IF", "VVS1", "VVS2"))
    & (color == "D")
    & (cut == "Ideal")
  )

ggplot(best_diamonds, aes(carat, price, colour = clarity)) +
  geom_point()
```

We can clearly see that when it comes to price IF > VVS1 > VVS2 for a given carat. We can also easily see that there aren't many diamonds between 0.75 and 1.0 carat. Moreover, above 1.0 carat the price difference between the three clarity levels increases, perhaps because such diamonds are rarer. The power of plots!

How about one more? Let's opt for a boxplot (AKA box-and-whisker diagram) this time since we have categorical (clarity, colour, cut) and continuous variables (carat, price). It'd be interesting to see to what extent colour affects price:

```{R}
coloured_diamonds <- diamonds %>%
  filter(
    (clarity %in% c("VVS2"))
    & (cut == "Ideal")
  ) %>%
  mutate(price_per_carat = price / carat)

ggplot(coloured_diamonds, aes(color, price_per_carat)) +
  geom_boxplot()
```

It seems like there isn't a strong trend here, although we can see that the D-F (colourless) diamonds are a bit pricier than the G-J (near-colourless) diamonds.

Now it's time for *you* to create some plots! 

Have some fun trying to visualise the following:

1.  How age and weight are distributed amongst the patients.
    a.  Can you also make it easy to see the difference between sexes on the same plot?

2.  How BMI may be related to response.
    a.  Does treatment group impact this relationship?

3.  How protein concentration is (or isn't) correlated with response.
    a.  And does treatment group impact this relationship?

## Modelling

::: {.callout-warning}
## Advanced task

This will require you to have some knowledge of mathematical modelling, so don't worry if you find it too tricky, you can skip it. [Chapters 22-25 of R for Data Science](https://r4ds.had.co.nz/model-intro.html) serve as a great introduction.
:::

Try to create a simple model, such as a *decision tree*, capable of predicting whether a given patient will respond or not.

A few considerations:

- You'll need to split the dataset into *training* and *test* data, the *caret* package can help here with its `createDataPartition()` function.
- Be sure to include only the columns which are relevant for modelling, e.g. subject_id can be safely discarded.
- For decision trees the package *rpart* is a good choice, along with *rpart.plot* to actually view a trained tree!
- A more sophisticated option is a *random forest*. This involves training a collection of decision trees, each on a different subset of the data, and then selecting the best one. Try the package *randomForest*.

Happy Modelling!
